SIMPLE: dint
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dint
<hw>Dint</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>dint</ets>,
<ets>dent</ets>, <ets>dunt</ets>, a blow, AS. <ets>dynt</ets>; akin to
Icel. <ets>dyntr</ets> a dint, <ets>dynta</ets> to dint, and perh. to L.
<ets>fendere</ets> (in composition). Cf. 1st <er>Dent</er>,
<er>Defend</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A blow; a stroke.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Mortal <xex>dint</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Milton.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Like thunder's <xex>dint</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Fairfax.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The mark left by a blow; an indentation or
impression made by violence; a dent.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every <qex>dint</qex> a sword had beaten in it [the shield].</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Force; power; -- esp. in the phrase <xex>by dint
of</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now you weep; and, I perceive, you feel⟦br⟧
The <qex>dint</qex> of pity.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was by <qex>dint</qex> of passing strength⟦br⟧
That he moved the massy stone at length.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dint</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Dint
<hw>Dint</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Dinted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Dinting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make a mark or cavity on or
in, by a blow or by pressure; to dent.</def> <rj><au>Donne.
Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dinumeration</ent>⟦br⟧
